mt-3"><p>The <span class=3D"cursor-pointer text-nowrap glossified-term" dat=
a-test-id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0">Beaufort scale</span>, officially k=
nown as the Beaufort <span class=3D"cursor-pointer text-nowrap glossified-t=
erm" data-test-id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0">wind</span> force scale, is=
 a descriptive table. It <span class=3D"cursor-pointer text-nowrap glossifi=
ed-term" data-test-id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0">depicts</span> the forc=
e of wind by a series of numbers, typically from 0 to 12. The Beaufort scal=
e goes all the way to 17, but the last five numbers only apply to <span cla=
ss=3D"cursor-pointer text-nowrap glossified-term" data-test-id=3D"glossifie=
d" tabindex=3D"0">tropical</span> <span class=3D"cursor-pointer text-nowrap=
 glossified-term" data-test-id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0">typhoons</span=
>. These numbers are only used in the areas around China and Taiwan.<br><br=
>The scale is named for <span class=3D"cursor-pointer text-nowrap glossifie=
d-term" data-test-id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0">Sir Francis Beaufort</sp=
an> of the British <span class=3D"cursor-pointer text-nowrap glossified-ter=
m" data-test-id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0">Royal Navy</span>. In 1805, h=
e devised a method of describing wind force according to <span class=3D"cur=
sor-pointer text-nowrap glossified-term" data-test-id=3D"glossified" tabind=
ex=3D"0">procedures</span> for setting sails on a <span class=3D"cursor-poi=
nter text-nowrap glossified-term" data-test-id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0=
">warship</span>.<br><br>The Beaufort scale is useful for estimating wind p=
ower without <span class=3D"cursor-pointer text-nowrap glossified-term" dat=
a-test-id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0">wind instruments</span>.<br><br>0: =
Calm and still winds. Smoke rises vertically.</p><p>1. Light winds at 1-5 k=
ph (1-3 mph). Smoke drift shows wind direction.</p><p>2. Light <span class=
=3D"cursor-pointer text-nowrap glossified-term" data-test-id=3D"glossified"=
 tabindex=3D"0">breeze</span> at 6-11 kph (4-7 mph). Wind can be felt on fa=
ce; flags <span class=3D"cursor-pointer text-nowrap glossified-term" data-t=
est-id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0">ripple</span>.</p><p>3. Gentle breeze =
at 12-19 kph (8-12 mph). Flags wave.</p><p>4. Gentle breeze at 20-28 kph (1=
3-18 mph). Paper and leaves scatter.</p><p>5. Fresh breeze at 29-38 kph (19=
-24 mph). Small trees sway; whitecaps form on waves.</p><p>6. Strong breeze=
 at 39-49 kph (25-31 mph). Umbrellas are hard to use; large branches on tre=
es move.</p><p>7. Moderate <span class=3D"cursor-pointer text-nowrap glossi=
fied-term" data-test-id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0">gale</span> at 50-61 =
kph (32-38 mph). Trees sway; walking in the wind is difficult.</p><p>8. Fre=
sh gale at 62-74 kph (39-46 mph). Twigs and branches break off trees.</p><p=
>9. Strong gale at 75-88 kph (47-54 mph). Roof tiles blow off buildings.</p=
><p>10. Whole gale at 89-102 kph (55-63 mph). Trees are <span class=3D"curs=
or-pointer text-nowrap glossified-term" data-test-id=3D"glossified" tabinde=
x=3D"0">uprooted</span>.</p><p>11. <span class=3D"cursor-pointer text-nowra=
p glossified-term" data-test-id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0">Storm</span> =
at 103-118 kph (64-73 mph). Widespread damage to <span class=3D"cursor-poin=
ter text-nowrap glossified-term" data-test-id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0"=
>vegetation</span> and buildings; there's nearly no visibility at sea.</p><=
p>12. <span class=3D"cursor-pointer text-nowrap glossified-term" data-test-=
id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0">Hurricane</span> at 119-220 kph (74-136 mp=
h). A Category 1 hurricane or a Category 1 <span class=3D"cursor-pointer te=
xt-nowrap glossified-term" data-test-id=3D"glossified" tabindex=3D"0">torna=
