re tropical storms that form in the Atlantic Ocean with wind speeds of at l=
east 119 kilometers (74 miles) per hour. Hurricanes have three main parts, =
the calm eye in the center, the eyewall where the winds and rains are the s=
trongest, and the rain bands which spin out from the center and give the st=
orm its size. Meteorologists use the Saffir-Simpson Hurricane Wind Scale to=
 classify hurricanes into categories one to five. Categories three to five =
are considered a major storm. A category five hurricane has wind speeds tha=
t exceed 252 kilometers (157 miles) per hour. Coastal areas are often most =
heavily impacted by the damaging winds, rains, and storm surges as the stor=
m collides with or brushes land.

